{
  "task_context": {
    "description": "This is a comparative electromagnetic calorimeter geometry study using Monte Carlo simulation to evaluate detector performance characteristics across three distinct topological designs. The task involves systematic testing of box, projective tower, and accordion calorimeter geometries using identical materials and layer configurations to isolate the impact of geometry on key performance metrics. The study requires measuring energy resolution, response uniformity across detector surfaces, shower containment, and energy linearity for each geometry using electron beams at multiple energy points. This is a controlled detector physics experiment designed to quantify how geometric design choices affect fundamental calorimeter performance parameters while maintaining all other variables constant.",
    "goal": "Determine which electromagnetic calorimeter geometry (box, projective tower, or accordion) provides the best combination of energy resolution and response uniformity, and assess how dead material effects vary between geometries",
    "constraints": [
      "Use exactly 3 configurations (one per topology)",
      "Use same materials for all geometries (lead absorber + plastic scintillator)",
      "Maintain consistent layer thicknesses across all designs",
      "Total depth must be approximately 20 radiation lengths",
      "Use tractable simulation parameters for computational feasibility"
    ]
  },
